Ready to unlock the power of Tegus? Trial the benefits for free now below:
1) Frontier buyers sign first $53M in offtake agreements with Charm Industr=
ial [ https://substack.com/redirect/bbcd9e8b-7941-4ef2-ae34-a4751b93c739?j=
=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
From Frontier
Frontier [ https://substack.com/redirect/aaf93ba6-bf89-46e3-a01b-adc9385c59=
5f?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] has=
 facilitated its first set of offtake agreements with Charm Industrial [ ht=
tps://substack.com/redirect/3b2c7de6-ce11-4438-845c-e5b65f853fd9?j=3DeyJ1Ij=
oiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], totaling $53M. =
Frontier buyers will pay Charm to remove 112,000 tons of CO=E2=82=82 from t=
he atmosphere and store them permanently underground between 2024 and 2030.
We=E2=80=99ve written about Frontier, the advance market commitment (AMC) f=
rom Stripe, Alphabet, Shopify, Meta, and McKinsey a few times since it was =
first announced. Frontier is most notable for two reasons: 1) its focus on =
carbon removal and 2) its =E2=80=9Cadvance commitment=E2=80=9D structure, w=
hich reflects a =E2=80=9Cif you fund it, they will come=E2=80=9D philosophy=
=2E
On Thursday, Frontier announced its first actual carbon offtake agreement w=
ith with Charm Industrial, totaling $53M. Charm, which is led by former Seg=
ment founder and CEO Peter Reinhardt, has a unique approach to carbon remov=
al. Charm Industrial converts biomass into a stable, carbon-rich liquid and=
 then pumps it deep underground, where it is stored permanently.
This is likely the first of many similar Frontier projects, as the AMC has =
committed over $1B to fund carbon removal projects. It currently has 16 org=
anizations in its portfolio that are taking novel approaches to carbon capt=
ure and removal.
(2) Seaflooding [ https://substack.com/redirect/5e202214-bb24-4e7d-a8d9-516=
7a07a5c83?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNp=
U ]
Tomas Pueyo [ https://substack.com/redirect/2c3ad4cf-9778-492a-9177-fe20425=
e84e9?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] =
for Unchartered Territories (h/t @TamarHaspel [ https://substack.com/redire=
ct/f9949dc7-ddcb-4eed-86b9-7938d8d8808b?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_Z=
lNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ])
Sea levels might rise by one to two meters by the end of the century.
What if I told you there was a way to mitigate that, while creating new hab=
itats and more life, growing the economy, and making money along the way?
Let=E2=80=99s call it seaflooding.
While Frontier funds carbon removal projects, even more creative solutions =
to climate change are being proposed =E2=80=94 like this one, dubbed =E2=80=
=9CSeaflooding=E2=80=9D from Tomas Pueyo. The general idea of Seaflooding i=
s to flood sub sea-level areas with water turning vast deserts into flouris=
hing (and energy producing) ecosystems. The top two candidates for such Sea=
flooding, according to Pueyo, are the Dead Sea and the Qattara Depression.
Here=E2=80=99s generally how it would work:
Build pipelines from a sea into a sub sea-level desert area
Generate electricity from the flow of seawater into desert area
Slowly a new, flourishing natural ecosystem develops
Infrastructure, communities, and economies follow
It=E2=80=99s tough to comprehend the scale, complexity, and timelines of a =
project like this, and frankly we=E2=80=99re not in a position to cast judg=
ement on its feasibility. But, at face-value, it seems like an idea that, i=
f properly executed, could both a) generate a cheap electricity and b) tran=
sform deserts into vibrant sealine communities.
(3) Mutation Protected Man From Alzheimer=E2=80=99s Disease, Hinting at Tre=
atment [ https://substack.com/redirect/b2283030-b5b4-4731-ad23-a24f51338fb6=
?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Gina Kolata [ https://substack.com/redirect/8ad9e92b-7a6a-4d86-8721-8792e2a=
64a5e?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] =
for The New York Times
More than six million [ https://substack.com/redirect/eaf70607-c36f-4c1a-97=
bb-59c54cde1810?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8=
ExkRNpU ] people in the United States have Alzheimer=E2=80=99s, a disease t=
hat has been notoriously difficult to treat. Yet here was a man with a muta=
tion that causes the most severe and rapidly progressing form of Alzheimer=
=E2=80=99s. And his disease was delayed for two decades. If a drug could do=
 what the mutation did, resulting in most people getting Alzheimer=E2=80=99=
s very late in life, the outcome could be transformative.
This story, from the NYT, is based on a new research paper [ https://substa=
ck.com/redirect/f1d1e5d3-34aa-4f27-8de5-fb224d3fcacd?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ=
=2Egb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8=
ExkRNpU ] published in Nature earlier=20=
this week. The paper investigates the unique story of a man who, according =
to all biomarkers, should have developed the symptoms of Alzheimer=E2=80=99=
s in his early 40s but did not show signs of the disease until he was well =
into his 60s. The development of his Alzheimer=E2=80=99s, which itself is c=
aused by a gene mutation, was stunted by a separate gene mutation which blo=
cked the disease from entering his entorhinal cortex.
The finding is important because if a drug could accomplish what this mutat=
ion did, it could delay the onset of Alzheimer=E2=80=99s for years and even=
 decades. Animal studies are already underway, but FDA approved drugs are l=
ikely years away. This is, of course, just one approach to delaying or curi=
ng Alzheimer=E2=80=99s =E2=80=94 but we=E2=80=99re encouraged by the number=
 of promising Alzheimer=E2=80=99s treatments coming out in just the last co=
uple of years.
(4) Researchers treat depression by reversing brain signals traveling the w=
rong way [ https://substack.com/redirect/e83dc633-e7b3-4b49-8948-cf3bc62e6d=
ec?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Nina Bai for Stanford Medicine News Center
Powerful magnetic pulses applied to the=C2=A0scalp to stimulate the brain=
=C2=A0can bring fast relief to many severely depressed patients for whom st=
andard treatments have failed. Yet it=E2=80=99s been a mystery exactly how =
transcranial magnetic stimulation, as the treatment is known, changes the b=
rain to dissipate depression. Now, research=C2=A0led by Stanford Medicine s=
cientists=C2=A0has found that the treatment works by reversing the directio=
n of abnormal brain signals.
Transcranial Magnetic Stimulation (TMS) has been used to treat major depres=
sive disorder since the late 1990=E2=80=99s, but researchers have just now =
discovered how exactly is works. New research from Stanford indicates that =
TMS works by works by reversing abnormal brain signals. The research found =
that the flow of activity between the anterior insula and the anterior cing=
ulate cortex is reversed, and this reversed flow correlates with the severi=
ty of depression. This is an important finding for two reasons:
It gives researchers a better understanding of how this treatment actually =
works.
the reversed flow could potentially serve as a biomarker for diagnosing and=
 triaging depression.
Generally TMS is a non-invasive and safe alternative treatment method for p=
atients that have not taken to medicine or psychotherapy.=20
(5) Is space the place for stem cell manufacturing? Scientists will soon te=
st that on the ISS [ https://substack.com/redirect/4af6b4a7-582d-4e06-bd12-=
6420f70416fb?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8Exk=
RNpU ]
Helen Floersh [ https://substack.com/redirect/51e52641-5817-46a9-b9bc-d2305=
0be3f69?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU =
] for Fierce Biotech
The world=E2=80=99s second-ever private astronaut mission to the Internatio=
nal Space Station will not only ferry up the first Saudi Arabian woman [ ht=
tps://substack.com/redirect/2e27fccd-86af-4a32-9c5c-e82f7088efe1?j=3DeyJ1Ij=
oiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] to go to space b=
ut also a first-of-its-kind experiment that will test whether scientists ca=
n create induced pluripotent stem cells, or iPSCs, in microgravity. The exp=
eriment is part of a series that could eventually lead to new ways to manuf=
acture stem cells en masse.
The most interesting stuff happens at the intersections. In this case, the =
intersection of space and biotech.
There=E2=80=99s already evidence that microgravity might be an ideal growin=
g ground for stem cells, and this mission is meant to give a team of medica=
l researchers a real-life 5 day view if that=E2=80=99s truly the case. Of c=
ourse, a mission like this is, at least in part, due to that drastic decrea=
se in launch costs brought on by SpaceX that makes a whole slew of new spac=
e endeavors possible.
Stem cells are particularly interesting because they can be reprogrammed in=
to any type of cell. But a whole slew of chemical and drug development proj=
ects could benefit from the unique characteristics of space. This idea, tha=
t manufacturing in microgravity is now both possible and advantageous, is t=
he core insight behind Not Boring Capital portfolio company Varda [ https:/=
/substack.com/redirect/54bca62a-32b5-4bff-945d-5f20e9332a11?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXA=
wZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. You=E2=80=99ll be he=
aring more about them soon.
Space drugs. Woah man.
BONUS: Not Boring Biotech Partner, Elliot Hershberg [ https://substack.com/=
redirect/0df0fcdd-ff39-49fd-9861-235823c95b45?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T=
7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], is attending and speaking at the S=
ynBioBeta Conference [ https://substack.com/redirect/cdc4119f-4161-4072-a7d=
5-1ab61e8eacd2?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8E=
xkRNpU ] from May 23 - May 26th in Oakland, CA. SynBioBeta is the largest s=
ynbio conference of the year and a great opportunity to learn from and meet=
 many of the leading researchers, operators, and investors in synbio today.=
=20
Prior to the conference, on May 21st, Not Boring is hosting an event with F=
ifty Years called =E2=80=9CViriditas Feast.=E2=80=9D [ https://substack.com=
/redirect/e5c68229-9dd9-4ddb-80ed-b5a8e260e2f0?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5=
T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] You can apply to attend!
EVENT DESCRIPTION: What if we could grow anything? How can we enable a beau=
tiful and abundant future for an expanding population? How can we manifest =
the Bioeconomy? These are some of the central questions for the growing fie=
ld of synthetic biology. Let=E2=80=99s explore answers to these questions t=
ogether. Join us at the Fifty Years HQ in San Francisco for an evening of f=
ood and conversation with a community of scientists and leaders from the bi=
ological frontier.
That=E2=80=99s all for this week. We=E2=80=99ll be back in your inbox on Mo=
nday.
Thanks for reading,
Dan

